          "id": 2,
          "text": "Circular stapler"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Curved stapler"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: A) <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">Linear</span> stapler</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p>The instrument shown in the image is a<strong> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">Linear</span> Stapler</strong>.</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>It consists of a handle, shaft, anvil, and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b4c96c9d01692777199d56349e8d8\">stapling</span> cartridge.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Uses: </strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Side to side anastomoses.</li>\n\t\t<li>Ends are closed by <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a6260fa86416927772008d36bd7e5f\">transverse</span> staple.</li>\n\t\t<li>To close the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> either completely or partially.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Linear Stapler\" data-author=\"ignis\" data-hash=\"12813\" data-license=\"CC BY SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Surgical_staplers#/media/File:Surgical_stapler_&_cutter_linear.JPG\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"228\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/e9Hts3IplcbamH3gvf3Q1747382931.png\" width=\"389\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Skin stapler</strong> <strong>(Option B)</strong> is used for closing skin wounds, not internal tissues, and does not create the straight-line <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"2b4569285f1692777184282b1ca3f1\">closure</span> typical of a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">linear</span> stapler.</p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Skin Stapler\" data-author=\"Steven Fruitsmaak\" data-hash=\"12814\" data-license=\"CC BY 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Surgical_staplers#/media/File:Skin_stapler_01.jpg\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"232\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/ys81WcK211qGlSNSDx1Q1747383038.png\" width=\"368\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Circular stapler, also called EEA stapler (End to End Anastomosis) (Option C)</strong> is used for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7fb96d08421692777181e532c3c653\">anastomosis</span> of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"98d387b7bd1692777201278b27be72\">tubular</span> structures like the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> or blood vessels, creating a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0919f0017e1692777184ac3748841f\">circular</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b4c96c9d01692777199d56349e8d8\">stapling</span> line. It is not suitable for straight-line stapling, which is the function of a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">linear</span> stapler.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"Circular stapler\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"12866\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"253\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/NiT9wjanz88th8kiFYwQ1747407757.png\" width=\"400\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Curved stapler</strong> <strong>(Option D)</strong> is used for hard-to-reach areas, typically in the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b3a647ce2516927771881427f56c1d\">gastrointestinal</span> tract, but like the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0919f0017e1692777184ac3748841f\">circular</span> stapler, it does not create a straight-line closure, which is the purpose of a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">linear</span> stapler.</p>",
