    {
      "text": "Which of the following are used to stop oesophagal variceal bleeding?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "A, B & C"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "A and B only"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "A, Band C"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "A, B and D"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: A) A, B & C </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>A) Sengstaken Blakemore Tube: (Option A)</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Its primary use is <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f6c884e91916927771829b26c9369a\">Balloon tamponade</span> for controlling <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d4607865bb1692777201a35341db81\">variceal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"41e858bf2816927771836d46c619b9\">bleeding</span> in the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"84f4cb0ade16927771940b83eacc37\">oesophagus</span> and stomach.</li>\n\t<li>It is also called a four-lumen Minnesota tube or Linton's tube or Modified 4 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e87def492e1692777191eda63cfc5e\">lumen</span> Pitcher tube.</li>\n\t<li>It contains a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"12347b15191692777188bc86d226e1\">gastric</span> balloon, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"192677035a169277718780b4d6dbbb\">esophageal</span> balloon, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"12347b15191692777188bc86d226e1\">gastric</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"831d67ad8a1692777182763ca62e4b\">aspiration</span> port and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"192677035a169277718780b4d6dbbb\">esophageal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"831d67ad8a1692777182763ca62e4b\">aspiration</span> port.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"Sengstaken Blackmore Tube\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"12145\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"224\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/OH0zdarcbW7eghN8WlkP1746518275.png\" width=\"400\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>B) Minnesota tube: (Option A) </strong>It is similar to the Sengstaken-Blakemore tube and is used to control upper GI bleeding, including oesophagal varices, by balloon tamponade.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"Minnesota Tube\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"12147\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"267\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/gpgzVXqTdDtBFimBX5hi1746518302.png\" width=\"400\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>C) Upper GI endoscopy: (Option A) </strong>It is a crucial tool in managing oesophagal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d4607865bb1692777201a35341db81\">variceal</span> bleeding. While it doesn't directly stop the bleeding, it allows for visualisation of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c3b47c6c6b16927772018ebcc5b5a9\">varices</span> and enables interventions such as <strong>band ligation</strong> or <strong>sclerotherapy</strong> to control the bleeding.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Upper GI Endoscopy \" data-author=\"Liedlgruber, M. & Uhl, Andreas\" data-hash=\"12149\" data-license=\"NA\" data-source=\"https://www.researchgate.net/figure/a-A-flexible-endoscope-Image-courtesy-of-Olympus-and-b-an-example-of-a-WCE-capsule_fig2_228576620\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"258\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/0kO3dRU25atHMnqR4Dc71746518329.png\" width=\"400\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>D) Monopolar cautery: </strong>It involves the use of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f41aa22f791692777187728e68c9e7\">electric current</span> to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b3062c0c8c16927771846dd0fc1343\">coagulate</span> and stop <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"41e858bf2816927771836d46c619b9\">bleeding</span> from varices. It can be used during <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"35ca8c2d5f16927771879351e8f97e\">endoscopic</span> procedures to target specific <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"41e858bf2816927771836d46c619b9\">bleeding</span> points.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Monopolar Cautery \" data-author=\"de:Benutzer:Kalumet\" data-hash=\"12151\" data-license=\"CC BY SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endoscopy#/media/File:Flexibles_Endoskop.jpg\" data-tags=\"May2025\" height=\"318\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/ZDPs59o2KHn84OjK8h0y1746518359.png\" width=\"400\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>",
